04496nam a22007695i 9781477300442DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015030235  a97814773004427 a10.7560/3095442doi  a(DE-B1597)587948  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aF3429.3.P34bC64 2016 4aF3429.3.P34C64 2016 7aART0440002bisacsh04a751.7309851 aCohen Suarez, Ananda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHeaven, Hell, and Everything in Between :bMurals of the Colonial Andes /cAnanda Cohen Suarez. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Painted Walls of the Andes -- t2. The Road to Hell Is Paved with Flowers -- t3. Clothing the Architectonic Body -- t4. Turning the Jordan River into a Pacarina -- t5. Earthly Violence/Divine Justice -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamining the vivid, often apocalyptic church murals of Peru from the early colonial period through the nineteenth century, Heaven, Hell, and Everything in Between explores the sociopolitical situation represented by the artists who generated these murals for rural parishes. Arguing that the murals were embedded in complex networks of trade, commerce, and the exchange of ideas between the Andes and Europe, Ananda Cohen-Aponte also considers the ways in which artists and viewers worked through difficult questions of envisioning sacredness. This study brings to light the fact that, unlike the murals of New Spain, the murals of the Andes possess few direct visual connections to a pre-Columbian painting tradition; the Incas’ preference for abstracted motifs created a problem for visually translating Catholic doctrine to indigenous congregations, as the Spaniards were unable to read Inca visual culture. Nevertheless, as Cohen Suarez demonstrates, colonial murals of the Andes can be seen as a reformulation of a long-standing artistic practice of adorning architectural spaces with images that command power and contemplation. Drawing on extensive secondary and archival sources, including account books from the churches, as well as on colonial Spanish texts, Cohen Suarez urges us to see the murals not merely as decoration or as tools of missionaries but as visual archives of the complex negotiations among empire, communities, and individuals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArt and societyzAndes RegionxHistory. 0aArtxPolitical aspectsxAndes RegionxHistory. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszAndes RegionxHistory. 0aIndian mural painting and decorationzAndes Region. 0aIndian mural painting and decorationzPeru (Viceroyalty) 0aIndian mural painting and decorationzPeru (Viceroyalty). 0aIndians of South AmericazAndes RegionxAntiquities. 0aIndians of South AmericazAndes RegionxReligion. 7aART / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30954440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477300442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477300442/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK